1 TASK1: DESeq analysis of APEX-tagged genes

In this assignment, you will analyze RNA-seq data from a recent paper. In this work, the authors developed a method termed APEX-RIP, which maps transcriptomes to sub cellular compartments based on proximity to a specific protein.

The four proteins used in this study are markers from different cellular locations:

  1. A mitochondrial protein (Mito),
  2. An ER membrane protein (KDEL-HRP),
  3. A nuclear localization sequence (NLS),
  4. A nuclear export sequence (NES).

For each of these fusions, RNAs labelled with biotin (“RIP”) were compared to a non-labelled background (“Input”), each with 2-3 replicates. The RNA-seq data were quantified using RSEM and gene annotations taken from RefSeq. The

The file “rsem_files_ex.txt” consists in a table, a.k.a Design Matrix, assigning each file within the zipped archive has a specific condition and replicate number.

Notes:

  • RSEM is an accurate and user-friendly software tool for quantifying transcript abundances from RNA-Seq data. RSEM implements an algorithm to assign reads to the isoforms from which they are more likely to be originated.
  • Therefore the transcript level is not to be mistaken for read counts. It is a quantitative estimation of transcript abundance given RNA-seq data.

1.1.1 Read the table “rsem_files_ex.txt” into an object called ftab.

This file catalogues RNA-seq experiments in the form of a table with 3 columns:
(i) The RSEM output file
(ii) Condition tested for each experiment
(iii) The number of the replicate

Load all the RSEM files into a variable called rse using tximport() and the ftabobject.

cdat <- data.frame(condition = as.factor(paste(ftab$V2, ftab$V3, sep = "_")), replicate = as.factor(ftab$V4))

cdat$condition <- gsub("-", "_", cdat$condition)

ds.txi <- DESeqDataSetFromTximport(txi = rse, colData = cdat, design = ~condition +
    replicate)

ds <- DESeq(ds.txi, betaPrior = T)

rows.keep <- rowSums(counts(ds)) > 10
dds <- ds[rows.keep, ]

retained <- sum(rows.keep)/length(ds.txi) * 100
removed <- (length(ds.txi) - sum(rows.keep))/length(ds.txi) * 100

ANSWER1 = paste0("In this dataset we have ", nrow(ds.txi), " genes with a length greater than 300")
ANSWER2 = paste0(round(removed, 2), "% genes were removed")
ANSWER3 = paste0(round(retained, 2), "% genes were retained")

1.3 Enrichment of differentially expressed genes per compartment

1.3.1 Find the number of significantly enriched genes in each compartment

Significantly enriched genes should have passed the statistical test on their fold-change expression between conditions (based on averaged across replicates) and yielded an adjusted p-value below the arbitrary threshold of 0.05.

The null hypothesis of the test is that the effect of the condition does not affect expression. Hence the fold-change of expression remains at 1 (or 0 on a log scale)

To access results from a DESeq analysis, use the results() function. Make sure to set the threshold for alpha to 0.05, specify in the contrast argument what should be compared (conditions or replicates) followed by the names of the conditions/replicates as specified in cdat. Hint: check the help of results for examples)

Extract the results of differential RNA expression for each compartment (Mito, ER, NLS, NES) between biotin-labelled (referred as ‘RIP’) vs. their respective background (referred to as ‘Input’).

Print the summary of each result objects to the console.

mito_contrast <- c("condition", "Mito_APEX2_RIP", "Mito_APEX2_Input")
er_contrast <- c("condition", "KDEL_HRP_RIP", "KDEL_HRP_Input")
nls_contrast <- c("condition", "NLS_APEX2_RIP", "NLS_APEX2_Input")
nes_contrast <- c("condition", "NES_APEX2_RIP", "NES_APEX2_Input")

You are asked to extract the number of genes with R commands so do not just write the number

num_DEGs_mito <- sum(mito_results$padj < 0.05 & abs(mito_results$log2FoldChange) >
    1, na.rm = TRUE)
num_DEGs_er <- sum(kdel_results$padj < 0.05 & abs(kdel_results$log2FoldChange) >
    1, na.rm = TRUE)
num_DEGs_nls <- sum(nls_results$padj < 0.05 & abs(nls_results$log2FoldChange) > 1,
    na.rm = TRUE)
num_DEGs_nes <- sum(nes_results$padj < 0.05 & abs(nes_results$log2FoldChange) > 1,
    na.rm = TRUE)


df <- data.frame(Compartment = c("Mito", "ER", "NLS", "NES"), Num_DEGs = c(num_DEGs_mito,

1.4 log2fold-change NLS vs. NES heat-scatterplot

Next, we want to evaluate the correlation for expression between different conditions. (e.g. NLS vs. NES).

Scatterplots are often misinterpreted whenever the density is not taken into account. The heatscatter() function from the LSD package solves this issue by estimating the points’ density and showing it as a color gradient.

1.4.1 HeatScatter plot

Use the log2FoldChange from the result object of both compartments (NLS vs NES) within the heatscatter() function. Make sure to display the correlation coefficient as the title using the correct parameter of the heatscatter() function, cor = TRUE.

Q4- What are the Pearson and Spearman correlation coefficients between the log2-fold changes in NLS and NES experiments?
> Hint: You can use the cor() function to calculate the r coefficient using both the “Spearman” and “Pearson” method
Save your answer in a variable ANSWER4

logFC_NLS <- nls_results$log2FoldChange
logFC_NES <- nes_results$log2FoldChange

pearson_corr <- cor(logFC_NLS, logFC_NES, method = "pearson")
spearman_corr <- cor(logFC_NLS, logFC_NES, method = "spearman")

ANSWER4 <- list(pearson_corr = pearson_corr, spearman_corr = spearman_corr)

2.2 Log transform the data

  2. If the data is not centered, center it by deducting the mean of each row from each value in that row.
  3. Save the log transform data and centered data in a variable cent_mat
log_data_sc <- log2(data_sc/10 + 1)

cent_mat <- t(apply(log_data_sc, 1, function(x) x - mean(x)))

2.3 QC The data

Calculate the complexity of each cell in the log_data (Apply the same calculation from weekly Ex.9).

  1. Keep cells with complexity larger than 500 and store the results in a variable comp_up
compute_comp <- function(tpm_data) {
    Complexity <- apply(tpm_data > 0, 2, sum)
    return(Complexity)
}

log_data_complexity <- compute_comp(log_data_sc)
comp_threshold <- 500
comp_up <- log_data_complexity > comp_threshold

  1. Filter cent_mat according to comp_up, keep cells with high complexity and save the filtered data set in cent_filt

  2. Filter metadata_sc according to comp_up, keep cells with high complexity and save the filtered data set in metadata_sc_filt

  3. Filter log_data according to comp_up, keep cells with high complexity and save the filtered data set in log_data_filt

2.6 Multiple comparisons of gene expression

2.6.1 Create a sample data

  1. Sample out randomly (using sample()) of the malignant cells, 536 cells.
  2. Store their names in variable sampled_malig
  3. Set replace = FALSE
  4. Store all non-Malignant cells into a variable called non_malignant.
  5. Remove all NA’s values from that variable.
set.seed(2020)  # Don't change!

sampled_malig <- sample(metadata_sc_filt$cell_name[metadata_sc_filt$Malignant ==
    "Malignant"], size = 536, replace = FALSE)
non_malignant <- metadata_sc_filt$cell_name[metadata_sc_filt$Malignant == "non-Malignant"]

non_malignant <- non_malignant[!is.na(non_malignant)]

2.6.2 Multiple t.test

For each gene, perform a t.test between the sampled malignant cells to the non_malignant cells using the cent_final matrix.

NOTICE! you will perform multiple test, you will need to use the HB FDR correction.

  1. Use the padjust function to apply FDR correction to the p-values from the multiple testing before.
  2. Save the p-values in a variable p_values and the adjusted p-values store in a vector named p_adjusted
malig_values <- cent_final[, sampled_malig]
non_malig_values <- cent_final[, non_malignant]

p_values = sapply(rownames(cent_final), function(x) {
    t.test(cent_final[x, sampled_malig], cent_final[x, non_malignant])$p.value
})

p_adjusted <- p.adjust(p_values, method = "fdr")
